      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown the beef and vegetables",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Melt {{unsalted-butter}} of butter in a large saucepan over a high heat. Brown the {{beef-shin}} beef pieces in batches until deeply coloured on all sides. Remove and set aside. Add the {{onion}}, {{carrot}}, and {{celery}} to the pan and cook over a medium heat for 8 minutes until beginning to colour.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add flour and simmer",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Stir in {{plain-flour}} of flour and cook for 2 to 3 minutes, stirring, until the flour smells slightly nutty and turns a light tan colour. Return the beef to the pan. Gradually add {{stock-beef}} of hot beef stock, stirring to prevent lumps. Add {{bay-leaves}}, thyme, {{worcestershire-sauce}}, {{sea-salt-flakes}}, and {{black-pepper}}. Bring to the boil, reduce to a gentle simmer, and cook partially covered for 1 hour to 1 hour 15 minutes until the beef is very tender. Remove the bay leaves and thyme sprigs before serving.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "The browning step is not optional. Colour on the beef and vegetables, and colour on the flour before adding the stock, are what produce the characteristic dark, savoury soup.",
              "cause": "Beef and vegetables not browned sufficiently, flour not cooked",
              "symptom": "Soup pale and grey"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Continue simmering. Beef shin needs at least an hour and sometimes longer depending on the size of the pieces. The meat should be pulling apart easily.",
              "cause": "Insufficient simmering time for the collagen in the shin to break down",
              "symptom": "Beef tough after an hour"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown Windsor soup was once a staple of British canteen food. It was served in hospitals, boarding schools, and railway dining cars from late Victorian times through the mid-1900s. The link to canteen food has stuck. But the home-cooked version, made with good beef and properly browned, is a different dish. It's a hearty winter soup with real depth of flavour.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
